  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT280-kilavi">kaḻaṟṟetirmaṟai. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Refusal against [the friend's] urging. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT280">
          <l> kēḷir vāḻiyō kēḷir nāḷumeṉ</l>
          <l> ṉeñcupiṇik koṇṭa vañci lōtip</l>
          <l> peruntōṭ kuṟumakaḷ ciṟumel lāka</l>
          <l> morunāḷ puṇarap puṇari</l>
          <l> ṉaraināḷ vāḻkkaiyum vēṇṭalaṉ yāṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Friends, may you live! Friends,</l>
          <l>if I can only unite <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> puṇara puṇariṉ </term>: is this a play on the double connotation of <term xml:lang="ta"> puṇar-tal </term>, bringing out the erotic connotation (to come together to copulate)? Or is it just a figura etymologica?</note> for one day</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with the small soft bosom <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	ākam </term> is taken in this case by Cām. as "body", but why not literally "bosom" as a <term xml:lang="la"> pars pro toto </term>? </note> of the little woman with big shoulders</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[and] pretty, few hair, who has laid my heart in fetters</l>
          <l rend="indent8">throughout the days,</l>
          <l>I won't need to live for [another] half day.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
